  <h1>Africa's Payment Fragmentation Crisis</h1>

  <p class="lead">
    Africa is home to 54 sovereign currencies, 8 monetary unions, and a rapidly expanding
    digital economy &mdash;yet cross-border payment costs remain among the highest in the world.
  </p>

  <h2>The Structural Problem</h2>

  <p>
    The average cost of sending money across African borders is <strong>8&ndash;12% of transaction
    value</strong> &mdash;more than double the global average. A Nigerian exporter paying a Ghanaian
    supplier loses a significant share of every transaction to correspondent banking fees,
    currency conversion spreads, and multi-day settlement windows. The fundamental cause is
    architectural: the continent lacks a shared digital currency standard.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>No unified CBDC layer:</strong> Each central bank operates independently with incompatible digital payment rails</li>
    <li><strong>Correspondent banking bottlenecks:</strong> Most AU corridors route through New York or London, adding cost and latency</li>
    <li><strong>Financial exclusion at scale:</strong> 57% of sub-Saharan Africa remains unbanked &mdash;excluded from formal digital payments entirely</li>
    <li><strong>Remittance drain:</strong> The continent loses an estimated $5B+ annually to remittance fees that would be near-zero on a shared protocol</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Why Existing Solutions Fall Short</h2>

  <p>
    Existing CBDC pilots &mdash;m-CBDC Bridge (BIS), Project Dunbar, mBridge &mdash;are designed
    for wholesale interbank settlement between central banks, not for retail bearer circulation
    accessible to individuals without bank accounts. Stablecoin alternatives introduce
    private-sector custody risk incompatible with sovereign monetary policy.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>
      <strong>The gap:</strong> There is currently no open-standard, central-bank-controlled
      <strong>CBDC</strong> that can be held and transferred by an individual without a bank
      account, across all 54 AU member state pairs, with cryptographic proof of authenticity.
      bearerCORE&#8482; fills this gap.
    </p>
  </div>

