  <h1>The bearerCORE&#8482; Protocol</h1>

  <p class="lead">
    bearerCORE&#8482; introduces a new class of digital monetary instrument: the
    <strong>CVIB</strong> (Central Bank Issuance Bill) &mdash;a cryptographically authenticated
    digital banknote issued exclusively by a licensed central bank, delivered to commercial
    banks as <strong>Digital Money Bundles</strong>.
  </p>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>

  <p>
    A CVIB is a PNG image file. Like a physical banknote, it carries denomination, issuer
    identity, serial number, and security features &mdash;embedded in the file itself using
    cryptographic primitives rather than ink and paper. The central bank's Ed25519 private
    key signs every CVIB at the moment of minting. No entity other than the issuing central
    bank can produce a valid CBDC unit.
  </p>

  <h3>Three-Layer Architecture</h3>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Issuance Layer (Central Bank):</strong> A hardened desktop minting station
      allows the Governor to initialize <strong>Digital Money Bundles</strong>. The system
      generates <strong>CVIB</strong> units, embeds encrypted metadata, and applies
      <strong>CBDC</strong>-grade Ed25519 cryptographic signatures before delivering packages
      via secure SFTP/NAS channels.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Validation Layer (Commercial Banks):</strong> An API-based validation desk
      ingests <strong>CVIB</strong> files to verify signature integrity and check against the
      National Registry. This layer ensures that every <strong>CBDC</strong> unit in
      circulation undergoes a full lifecycle audit &mdash;from initial minting to final redemption.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Corridor Layer (Cross-Border Settlement):</strong> A specialised engine manages
      FX rate resolution and liquidity pool backing across all 54 African Union corridors.
      This layer enforces the <strong>Economic Sovereignty</strong> of participating nations
      by ensuring that all issued <strong>CVIBs</strong> are backed 1:1 by locked reserves
      within the specified trade corridor.
    </li>
  </ul>

